FIX FOR "MY PHOTOS" CRASH: Go to Gallery (or Photos, whichever you use) app settings, go to "Set as default" and select "Clear defaults". Don't worry, this won't affect the data it holds in any way, and also you can reset it as default afterwards. Then, when you try to buy the "My photos" item, a prompt will appear asking you which app you want to use. Simply press the back button, and the prompt should disappear and the item should be bought. Hope this helped. Great game otherwise!

The core concept is fun; but it's the unique ambiance and story that kept me coming back. This is not a fast paced game. Instead, it builds on itself slowly, adding little things, while maintaining a sense of desolation that makes the question of what and why burn harder and harder. Because of the limits you become attached to what you have, and invested in reaching the end. It's a true rarity in terms of style, and enjoyable still in its simplicity.

It's not obvious by reading the description or watching the demo video, but this is a sort of puzzle/collection game, where one collects various combinations of items and burns them. There is no time limit, no IAPs, and there is an endless amount of in-game money to buy things to burn. Beware, however, that one needs native-level language skills (in the language they run the game in) and a good vocabulary (i.e. not a 5-year old) in order to figure out the hints left for collecting the proper combinations. Non-native speakers and children will probably just be frustrated or will have to settle for burning things at random until they stumble across combos. Ironically, this game causes my N7v2 to heat up considerably (no joke!). Has a minor control problem or two, e.g. certain items are very difficult to pick up from the first slot.
Note 2

content: As soon as I recognized the art style from World Of Goo I knew I was going to have this. It is a truly excellent example of how games for mobile should be done - slightly higher cost to begin with, but no in-app purchases, no forced Facebook connector, no "wait 5 hours for a life" etc. Soundtrack, graphics, addictive gameplay...what more do you want? One downside is that it chews through battery like anything - after a 90 minute session (yes, I played non-stop) my battery on my Xperia Z1 dropped from 95% to 54%. It would also be nice to spend the in-game money on hints for the combos - say 50c to reveal one of the items in the combo. Still, excellent game, highly reccomended.
